 is a 1992 one-on-one, weapon-based fighting arcade game developed and published by Allumer. It is the sequel to the 1986 arcade game, Gladiator. Along with Strata's Time Killers, Blandia is one of the earliest weapon-based fighting games modeled after its competitor Capcom's 1991 arcade hit Street Fighter II, but later became overshadowed by the success of SNK's 1993 weapon-based fighting game, Samurai Shodown.","popularity":1.333333333333333,"games":[56987,64309,43810,1235,41828,68324,41819,19698,80387,64081],"tags":[268435460,536871019,536871208],"category":0,"keywords":[107,296],"genres":[4],"first_release_date":703036800000,"platforms":[52],"release_dates":[{"category":0,"platform":52,"date":703036800000,"region":8,"human":"1992-Apr-12","y":1992,"m":4}],"cover":{"url":"//images.igdb.com/igdb/image/upload/t_thumb/bpph0zk5wa4pucjolgyi.jpg","cloudinary_id":"bpph0zk5wa4pucjolgyi","width":300,"height":213}},{"id":39877,"name":"Bio-Ship Paladin","slug":"bio-ship-paladin","url":"https://www.igdb.com/games/bio-ship-paladin","created_at":1498463794000,"updated_at":1515797733649,"summary":"Bio-ship Paladin, known in Japan as Space Battleship Gomora (宇宙戦艦ゴモラ?), is a 1990 horizontally scrolling shoot 'em up arcade game. It was later ported to the Sega Mega Drive. While the game is essentially a standard horizontally scrolling shoot 'em up, it has an innovation that makes it unique in the genre. The player flies a spaceship (specifically, a bioship) which has the standard forward guns to be found in all horizontal scrollers, but it also possesses a weapon that can be manually targeted with a crosshair, in the same manner as in the game Missile Command. This allows the player to fire in any direction with pinpoint accuracy, and adds an extra level of strategy to the game. The game saw an almost arcade perfect port on the Sega Mega Drive. What few changes there were actually enhanced the look of the game such as added parallax scrolling backgrounds in level 2.","popularity":1